英國諾福爾可特易福德","Twyford, Breckland, Norfolk, England":"英國英格蘭諾福爾可特易福德","lifeSummary":"當Sir Robert “Poppy” Pope, Esq. of Twyford於1385年出生在英國諾福爾可特易福德時，他的父親Robert Pope25歲，母親Mrs. Robert Pope24歲。他於1436年與Ann Mordox在英國素可蕾托 霍斯特德結婚。他們至少是2個兒子的父母。他去世於1497年在他的家鄉享年112歲。"},"zh-hans":{"1385–1497":"1385年–1497年","1387–1470":"1387年–1470年","1438–1470":"1438年–1470年","1441–1479":"1441年–1479年","1360–Male":"1360年–殁","1361–Female":"1361年–殁","1436":"1436年","1479":"1479年","1455":"1455年","1497":"1497年","1387":"1387年","1441":"1441年","1385":"1385年","1361":"1361年","1470":"1470年","1360":"1360年","1438":"1438年","Little Horsted, Sussex, England":"英国素可蕾托 霍斯特德","Little Horsted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"英国素可蕾托 霍斯特德","Buxted, Sussex, England":"英国素可布可泰德","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"英国諾福爾可特易福德","Twyford, Breckland, Norfolk, England":"英国英格兰諾福爾可特易福德","lifeSummary":"当Sir Robert “Poppy” Pope, Esq. of Twyford于1385年出生在英国諾福爾可特易福德时，他的父亲Robert Pope25岁，母亲Mrs. Robert Pope24岁。他于1436年与Ann Mordox在英国素可蕾托 霍斯特德结婚。他们至少是2个儿子的父母。他去世于1497年在他的家乡享年112岁。"},"hr":{"1385–1497":"1385.–1497.","1387–1470":"1387–1470.","1438–1470":"1438.–1470.","1441–1479":"1441.–1479.","1360–Male":"1360–preminuo","1361–Female":"1361–preminula","1436":"1436.","1479":"1479.","1455":"1455","1497":"1497.","1387":"1387","1441":"1441.","1385":"1385.","1361":"1361","1470":"1470.","1360":"1360","1438":"1438.","Little Horsted, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Little Horsted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Buxted, Sussex, England":"Buxted, Sussex, England","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, England","Twyford, Breckland, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1385–1497":"1385–1497","1387–1470":"1387–1470","1438–1470":"1438–1470","1441–1479":"1441–1479","1360–Male":"1360–Zesnulý","1361–Female":"1361–Zesnulá","1436":"1436","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1497":"1497","1387":"1387","1441":"1441","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1470":"1470","1360":"1360","1438":"1438","Little Horsted, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, Anglie","Little Horsted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, Anglie","Buxted, Sussex, England":"Buxted, Sussex, Anglie","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, Anglie","Twyford, Breckland, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1385–1497":"1385–1497","1387–1470":"1387–1470","1438–1470":"1438–1470","1441–1479":"1441–1479","1360–Male":"1360–Afdød","1361–Female":"1361–Afdød","1436":"1436","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1497":"1497","1387":"1387","1441":"1441","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1470":"1470","1360":"1360","1438":"1438","Little Horsted, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Little Horsted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Buxted, Sussex, England":"Buxted, Sussex, England","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, England","Twyford, Breckland, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1385–1497":"1385–1497","1387–1470":"1387–1470","1438–1470":"1438–1470","1441–1479":"1441–1479","1360–Male":"1360–Overleden","1361–Female":"1361–Overleden","1436":"1436","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1497":"1497","1387":"1387","1441":"1441","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1470":"1470","1360":"1360","1438":"1438","Little Horsted, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Little Horsted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Buxted, Sussex, England":"Buxted, Sussex, England","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, England","Twyford, Breckland, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1385–1497":"1385–1497","1387–1470":"1387–1470","1438–1470":"1438–1470","1441–1479":"1441–1479","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1361–Female":"1361–Deceased","1436":"1436","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1497":"1497","1387":"1387","1441":"1441","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1470":"1470","1360":"1360","1438":"1438","Little Horsted, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Little Horsted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Buxted, Sussex, England":"Buxted, Sussex, England","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, England","Twyford, Breckland, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pope,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>pope</i> (derived via Old English from Late Latin <i>papa</i> ‘bishop, pope’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’, in origin a nursery word.) In the early Christian Church, the Latin term was at first used as a title of respect for male clergy of every rank, but in the Western Church it gradually came to be restricted to bishops, and then only to the bishop of Rome; in the Eastern Church it continued to be used of all priests (see   Popov  ,   Papas  ). The nickname would have been used for a vain or pompous man, or for someone who had played the part of the pope in a pageant or play. The surname is also present in Ireland and Scotland.","North German: variant of   Poppe  .","German: translation of   Pabst  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Popov","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Nikolay, Oleg, Grigoriy, Anatoly, Andrei, Arkadi, Dmitriy, Mikhail, Sergey.  Bulgarian or Macedonian Atanas, Dimitar, Yordan.  Serbian Bosko, Bozidar, Branko.","Russian, Bulgarian, Macedonian, Serbian, and Rusyn: patronymic from <i>pop</i> ‘priest’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’ (compare English   Pope  ). The name may sometimes derive from a nickname, but celibacy was not enjoined on priests of the Orthodox Church and so the name can indeed mean ‘son of the priest’. In many cases, however, the Russian name means no more than ‘of the priest’ and designates a servant of a priest. Compare   Popoff  , see also   Pop   2,   Popovic  , and   Popovski   1.","Jewish (American): most likely a shortened form of   Popovski   2. Compare   Popoff  ."]},{"name":"Papke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Bernhard, Erwin, Hans, Otto, Willi.","North German (also <b>Päpke</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Low German <i>pape</i>, Dutch <i>paepe</i> ‘pope’. Compare   Pope  ."]}]},{"name":"Esq.","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone living on or owning land that was waterlogged or partly surrounded by water, from Middle Low German <i>es</i> ‘swamp, water’.","Swiss German: from the topographic name <i>Ess</i> ‘grazing area, pasture’.","Swiss German: from a vernacular short form of the personal name   Oswald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Esse","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farmstead Ese in Sogn of unexplained etymology, or Esse in Telemark, named with Old Norse <i>æsin</i> ‘hill’ + <i>-e</i> from <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’.","German: variant of   Ess  , or a topographic name from the river name Esse in Hesse."]},{"name":"Oswald","meanings":["Scottish (Fife and Lanarkshire), northern English, German, and French (mainly Alsace and Lorraine): from an Old English personal name composed of the elements <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>weald</i> ‘power’. In the Middle English period, this fell together with the less common Old Norse cognate <i>Ásvaldr</i>. The name was introduced to Germany from England, as a result of the fame of Saint Oswald, a 7th-century king of Northumbria, whose deeds were reported by Celtic missionaries to southern Germany. The name was also borne by a 10th-century English saint of Danish parentage, who was important as a monastic reformer. Veneration of Saint Oswald, the king, spread from the German lands to the neighbouring Slavic lands as well. The surname in the (German) spelling <i>Oswald</i> is thus also found especially in Czechia and Slovakia, while in North America it also absorbed various Slavic forms (see 3 below).","Irish (Down): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> (see   Hussey   1).","Americanized form of Slovenian, Slovak, and Czech <b>Osvald</b>, Slovenian and Slovak <b>Ožvald</b> or <b>Ozvald</b>, and probably also of Slovenian <b>Ožbolt</b>: from vernacular forms of the German personal name <i>Oswald</i>, of Old English origin (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Twyford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places calledTwyford, for example in Berkshire, Buckinghamshire, Derbyshire,Hampshire, Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, and Norfolk, fromOld English <i>twī-</i> ‘double’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[{"name":"Twiford","meanings":["English: variant of   Twyford  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":70,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert “Poppy” Pope, Esq. of Twyford was born in 1385, in Twyford, Norfolk, England, his father, Robert Pope, was 25 and his mother, Mrs. Robert Pope, was 24. He married Ann Mordox in 1436, in Little Horsted, Sussex, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1497, in his hometown, at the age of 112."},"et":{"1385–1497":"1385–1497","1387–1470":"1387–1470","1438–1470"